>https://pastebin.com/QZLKBANu
Alright, Fritewag here, here's my thoughts:
Spellchecking and a little more punctuation needed. It's mostly missing S'es ('consist' on the fourth line should be 'consists', 'taste' on the fifth line should be 'tastes' and so on). Also, you put apostrophes where they aren't needed sometimes. "Antho's" should be "anthros" the first few times you use that word. Whenever you use an apostrophe before an S, try to think of it as two words. "Anthro's" is essentially a shortened version of "Anthro is". However (and here's where it gets confusing for some people) It can also be used to refer to something which belongs to the noun in question. I.E. if we were referring to, I don't know, a drink which belonged to the anthro, it would be "the Anthro's Dr. Pepper". When referring to anthros in a general, plural term like you're doing in your green, it should be "Anthros".
I know, it's confusing. It takes a lot of people time to wrap their heads around it.

Describing:
Don't be afraid to mix things up a little. You use "Brown type fur" to refer to the bat's fur. It couldn't hurt to be a little more descriptive. It helps draw the reader in, after all. Personally, I find that the word "like" or the phrase "as if" is a life-saver when it comes to this. I.E. "She was a warm, golden brown, as if there were sunlight trapped in her fur". Don't be afraid to get creative. Also, and this is just me talking, don't rely on exact measurements so much. Instead of saying "she was 6ft 2 inches" or whatever, you could say "she towered over us all, a titan of a woman" or something. Using exact measurements all the time sounds a little too mechanical.

Characterisation:
Done fairly well, for the most part.

You definitely want to read through it and hammer out the dents, though. Read it back to yourself, ask yourself whether or not it sounds okay, and if it doesn't, replace it with something that does.
